title A real bug caught live -- HAWM0's own boot worker killed the emulator it just proved GREEN
prompt Keaton reported "the emulator isn't booting" after running tools/hawm0_boot_onpath_host.rish twice (both printed a clean GREEN close) and then tools/hawm1_sala_witness.rish immediately after, which reported no emulator attached both times.
think Read the two screenshots side by side rather than assuming the emulator genuinely failed to boot -- both HAWM0 runs printed a full, correct GREEN close (model=sdk_gphone64_x86_64, boot_completed after 1s the second time, real device props read back) immediately followed in the same terminal by HAWM1's own honest "no emulator attached" refusal. A device that boots clean and is then immediately gone is a teardown bug, not a boot failure -- the symptom named by the user ("isn't booting") was the visible surface of a different root cause.
think Reread tools/hawm0_boot_worker.sh's own cleanup logic rather than guessing: `trap cleanup EXIT` arms at the moment the emulator is launched in the background, and nothing in the script ever disarmed it before the script's own normal, successful exit at the very bottom (after printing the device: and GREEN: lines). Bash's own EXIT trap fires on every exit path, success included -- so the very last thing every "successful" run of this script did was quietly kill the emulator it had just spent 180 seconds proving GREEN, before any caller (adb, or HAWM1's own witness) got a chance to reach it.
think This was my own design mistake from the prior turn's HAWM0 script, not something Keaton did wrong or a flake in the tooling -- named that plainly in the fix rather than hedging. The trap's original intent (never leave a broken half-booted emulator running after a failed attempt) was sound; the bug was applying it unconditionally to every exit rather than only the failure paths.
think Fixed with the smallest correct change: insert `trap - EXIT` (disarm) immediately before the device-identity readback and the final GREEN print, so a successful run reaches the end with the trap already cleared and the emulator simply stays up. Every earlier `exit 1` failure branch still has the trap live, so a genuinely broken boot still tears itself down exactly as before -- the fix narrows the trap's own scope to failure paths only, rather than removing safety net entirely.
think Added tools/hawm0_stop.sh as the new explicit teardown, since the boot script no longer self-terminates on success and a runner would otherwise have no clean way to release the KVM/CPU resources once actually done -- adb -s emulator-5554 emu kill as the graceful path, a bare pkill fallback only if adb itself can't reach it, and an "already stopped" no-op check first so it is safe to run even with nothing up.
think Named the correct sequence explicitly in the docs going forward, since the fix changes a real operational habit: boot hawm0, then run hawm1's witness (or anything else) while it stays up in the same terminal session, then stop it deliberately when actually done -- rather than the old, broken assumption that each script call was self-contained and cleaned up after itself.
obs Worth naming honestly rather than glossing over: this bug shipped in the prior turn's own commit, reviewed and syntax-checked and even run inside this jail (where it correctly refused at the /dev/kvm assert, since this jail has no device to boot) -- the in-jail test proved the Rish entrypoint's own logic correct, yet never could have caught this bug, since the failure only manifests once a real emulator actually finishes booting successfully, which only ever happens on the host terminal this jail cannot reach. A real lesson for scripts split across a jail/host boundary this way: the jail's own test coverage has a structural blind spot at exactly the boundary it cannot cross, and that gap needs naming rather than assuming the in-jail test was sufficient.
file tools/hawm0_boot_worker.sh -- inserted `trap - EXIT` immediately before the device-identity readback and GREEN print; header comment names the bug, its root cause, and that Keaton hit it live
file tools/hawm0_stop.sh -- new; explicit graceful-then-fallback teardown for a running hawm0, syntax-checked
file context/specs/two-dev-environments-and-mobile-emulation.md -- HAWM1 rung's own citation gains the bugfix note and the new stop script
file work-in-progress/TASKS.md -- new dated bullet naming the bug, its exact root cause, the fix, and the corrected operational sequence
file work-in-progress/ROADMAP.md -- new dated paragraph naming the bug plainly as a real design mistake caught live, not a user error
recommend keep-going -- Keaton's own next action is unchanged in shape, only now actually reliable: boot hawm0, then run hawm1_sala_witness.rish in the same terminal session while it stays up, and the emulator will actually still be there this time.
